      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "32cf1e62_f11b2a45",
        "filename": "src/sksl/SkSLMetalCodeGenerator.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 740,
      "author": {
        "id": 8173
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-06-06T20:27:05Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I\u0027m a little confused. I thought we agreed yesterday to just pack the float3s? As for why it needs to be packed it\u0027s not just for alignment, it\u0027s mainly because packed_float3 has size 12 while float3 has size 16 in MSL. float3 has size 12 in SkSL, so things with alignment 4 after a float3 will have an layout offset of +12, which means the float3 will need to be packed on the MSL side. The other vectors float2 and float4 have the same size in MSL and SkSL, so this problem isn\u0027t encountered. I think the check for offset specification is leftover from when I was checking to pack other types that aren\u0027t float3s, so I will remove it since it doesn\u0027t seem to make a difference now.",
      "parentUuid": "eef8c188_650a28e4",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 735,
        "startChar": 7,
        "endLine": 740,
        "endChar": 9
      },
      "revId": "9034332a4575c5309954c9e079c12a8c337ad10d",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "e63636d6_3558a0da",
        "filename": "src/sksl/SkSLMetalCodeGenerator.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 740,
      "author": {
        "id": 5640
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-06-06T20:52:23Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "My question isn\u0027t really \"why are we packing float3\" - I get that we need to do that because Skia is packing float3.\n\nI guess my questions are:\n\n1) Why does float3 have an alignment of 4, but float2 have an alignment of 8? That just cannot be right. Perhaps I\u0027m misreading the code...?\n\n2) Do we need the \"packed\" flag in the MemoryLayout at all? There doesn\u0027t seem to be a case in which we *don\u0027t* pack the fields, so why specify it?\n\n3) Why treat float3 differently in the first place? It seems like a simple formula would give you the right size and alignment for all of the vector types without having to specifically check anywhere if it had 3 columns.\n\n4) Does the Metal memory layout actually differ from k430_Standard, and if so, how? I wonder if we just need to tell our Vulkan backend to use 430 instead of 140.\n\nIt\u0027s entirely possible that one or more of these are stupid questions - I\u0027m feeling a bit under the weather today, so maybe I\u0027m just being a bit slower than usual :-).",
      "parentUuid": "32cf1e62_f11b2a45",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 735,
        "startChar": 7,
        "endLine": 740,
        "endChar": 9
      },
      "revId": "9034332a4575c5309954c9e079c12a8c337ad10d",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "70489556_4dc68b48",
        "filename": "src/sksl/SkSLMetalCodeGenerator.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 740,
      "author": {
        "id": 8173
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-06-06T21:14:53Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "To be clear, SkSL shaders generated by Skia are not packing float3s, I\u0027m packing float3s during the conversion to MSL.\n\n1) float3 has alignment of 16. I\u0027m not packing to address alignment issues of the float 3 though. I\u0027m packing to address the alignment of what comes after it, if what comes after has an alignment of 4.\n\n2) Technically I don\u0027t have to have the packed flag in MemoryLayout since the float3s are all getting packed anyway, but I don\u0027t know if that\u0027s a better solution. What if eventually we have unpacked float3s?\n\n3) This goes back to my example from yesterday. A lot of the input SkSL code is like:\n\ninterface {\n    layout (offset \u003d 0) half3 A;\n    layout (offset \u003d 12) half B;\n}\n\nI feel like my code for handling this is very simple. It just asks is there a float3? If yes, pack; if not, don\u0027t pack. \n\n4) The size of a float3 in MSL is 16 bytes. The size of a float3 in 140 and 430 is 12 bytes. Alignment is the same at 16 bytes. I\u0027m guessing a lot of SkSL code is generated with the assumption that float3 size is only 12 bytes, so the next offset is +12 from the float3\u0027s offset. This will cause problems with Metal unless I write packed_float3 which then has size of 12 bytes. The fact that the packed_float3\u0027s alignment is now 4 bytes should be inconsequential, since I\u0027ve already ensured that I\u0027m writing the float3 at the offset location specified in the SkSL layout.\n\nHope you feel better tomorrow!",
      "parentUuid": "e63636d6_3558a0da",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 735,
        "startChar": 7,
        "endLine": 740,
        "endChar": 9
      },
      "revId": "9034332a4575c5309954c9e079c12a8c337ad10d",
